ITU Graphics Programming

Exercise 9 - Post-processing

Learning objectives

In this exercise we will practice some simple post-processing effects. We will be learning how to:

  • Control the exposure of the image.
  • Adjust the contrast, saturation and hue of the final result.
  • Blur the rendered image.
  • Intensify the highlights with bloom.
  • Implement cel-shading in a different way, with a thin outline.
References
  • LearnOpenGL - HDR: https://learnopengl.com/Advanced-Lighting/HDR
  • LearnOpenGL - Bloom: https://learnopengl.com/Advanced-Lighting/Bloom
  • glTexImage2D function: https://www.khronos.org/registry/OpenGL-Refpages/gl4/html/glTexImage2D.xhtml
Initial implementation

This is the last exercise for the renderer with the car scene.

As an alternative to the exercise from last week, this time we have implemented the same PBR lighting model using deferred rendering.

There are minor changes (like removing the glass), but the result is mostly the same. We also added emissive light for the car brake lights, just so you can see some emissive, but it is badly hardcoded in the shader.

In this implementation, we are adding a new render target: the accumulation buffer. This will be the target for the lighting passes, where we will store the lighting in HDR before copying to the default framebuffer.

We will take advantage of this while rendering the geometry and we will compute the ambient in this stage. No need to do a full screen pass for ambient later!

The accumulation buffer is also a good way to add emissive light while rendering the geometry.

Take some time to read the code before starting the exercise.

During the exercise we will be adding a few fullscreen passes with the following structure:.

  • Select the shader we want to use and assign it to variable shader.
  • Call function use() to set as the active shader.
  • Bind the target frame buffer (except if we are rendering to the default framebuffer, the screen).
  • Set the uniforms.
  • Call the function drawFullscreenPass() with the name of the main source texture (we will be using "SourceTexture") and the texture. This function will bind the texture as the first texture and draw a quad in the entire screen.
  • Unbind the frame buffer.
Exercise 9.1
 High Dynamic Range (HDR)

HDR allows the framebuffer to store values not clamped between 0 and 1. This is useful for example to handle scenes with very dark and very bright areas.

We will change the renderer to support HDR and will apply tone-mapping at the end to map to the range (0, 1).
For the tone-mapping we will use a fixed exposure that we can modify from the UI.

In main.cpp:

  • The first step is to use a texture format that allows floating point values. Find the gAccum texture in the code and change the texture format to 16 bit floating point. You will have to specify the internal format and the component type (float). You should not see any changes yet, but the internal texture contains values that are not clamped to (0, 1).
  • Now let's do the tone-mapping as a post-processing pass. Find the composition pass (the one where we do the final adjustments to the image) and change the shader used there from copy to compose.
  • We will need an exponent variable in the Config structure. This will be a floating point value that controls the global brightness of the image, with default value of 1.0f. Add it to the UI as well, so you can modify in runtime.
  • Pass the exponent uniform to the shader.

In compose.frag:

  • Add the uniforms that you just added in C++.
  • Transform the hdr color to the range (0, 1) with the formula explained in the lecture, using the exponent uniform.

You can now see the image in different exposure levels. Try changing the intensity of the lights and adjust the exposure to see the effect.
Exercise 9.2
Color grading

Video games usually need to apply post-processing after rendering the scene, to achieve a specific artistic look. We won't implement any advanced color grading filters, just some basic controls to understand how the image gets processed.

The filters we are going to implement will allow you to: adjust contrast, shift hue, adjust saturation and tint the image with a color.

We don't need new passes, all the filters will be implemented in compose pass.

In main.cpp, you will only need to add settings to the configuration and the UI for each filter:

  • For contrast: A float representing a contrast multiplier. Default value will be 1.0f. A good range for it can be from 0.5 to 1.5.
  • For hue shift: A float between -0.5 and 0.5, representing a hue shift. The shift is cyclic, so a hue shift of 0.5 is the same as -0.5. Default value is 0.
  • For saturation: A float value representing the relative saturation. Default value is 1.0f, values greater than that will have more saturated colors, less than that will be closer to gray.
  • For color filter: A color to tint the entire image. Default value is white.

In compose.frag:

  • Add the uniforms that you just added in C++.
  • All the filters will be applied to the color read from the texture, after the tone-mapping.
  • For contrast: Substract gray color from the current color value. Multiply the result by contrast uniform and add the same gray again. Clamp the result between 0 and 1.
  • For hue shift: Convert the color to HSV format. Modify the hue (x component) by adding the hue shift and taking only the fractional part (fract). Convert the color back to RGB.
  • For saturation: Compute the color luminance and substract it (as a vec3) from the current color value. Multiply the result by saturation uniform and add the luminance again. Clamp the result between 0 and 1.
  • For color filter: Just multiply the current color by the filter color.
Exercise 9.3
Blur

Blur post-processing consists in averaging the pixel color with the neighbors.
In this implementation we will use a gaussian distribution with a 9x9 kernel.

Gaussian filters are separable, which means we can do 2 passes with one-dimensional kernels (9x1 + 1x9) instead of 1 pass with two-dimensional kernel (9x9), for performance reasons.

In main.cpp:

  • We are going to need 2 new framebuffers, with the same size and format as the accumulation buffer. Find the function where we are creating frame buffers and implement the missing parts.
  • As we mentioned, we will do 2 passes for blur, one horizontal, one vertical. Each pass will take the image from one of the temporary framebuffers and put the result in the other. It is not possible to read and write to the same texture in the shader. This part is already implemented but take some time to understand the code.
  • Initially the blur passes are inside a for loop with 0 iterations. Change the number of iterations to 1 to enable blurring.
  • Finally, to visualize the result you will have to change the source image of the compose pass to be the first temporary buffer, that is holding the blurred image, instead of the accumulation buffer.

This time you don't have to change anything in the shader, but please take a look and ask questions if there is something you don't understand.

One important thing to notice here is how the result image ends in the same texture that it was before blurring. Because of this, we can apply the process many times to get a blurrier image (that is why we placed a for loop in there). Change the number of iterations in the loop and observe the results.
Exercise 9.4
Bloom

Now that we have implemented blur, we can use it to implement one of the main HDR post-effects: Bloom.

As seen in the lecture, we need to detect those areas that are too bright, blur them, and add them to the scene.

In main.cpp:

  • Change the copy shader to the bloom shader.
  • Add some configuration variables, add the values to the UI and set them as uniforms:
    • bloom threshold: float value that will set the luminance level for the pixels to start blooming. Default value can be 1.0f
    • bloom scale: multiplier to control the effect intensity. Default value will be 1.0f
    • bloom max intensity: maximum luminance value that will be added to the image. We can start with a value of 5.0f.

In bloom.frag:

  • Add the uniforms that you just added in C++.
  • Compute the luminance of the color value read from the texture.
  • Divide the color by the luminance. We do this because later we are going to multiply by the luminance again, once we get the right intensity.
  • Substract the threshold to the luminance. Values under the threshold will be black, above the threshold will be visible.
  • Clamp the luminance between 0 and the maximum intensity. This will avoid having pixels that are way too bright.
  • Scale the luminance value. This allows us to control the amount of light that we add to the scene
  • Return the color multiplied by the luminance.

Now you can see the blurred parts that will get added to the image. We want to add this during the compose pass. There are some steps left to do.

In main.cpp:

  • Change the source texture used by the compose pass back to the accumulation buffer.
  • Bind tempTextures[0] as GL_TEXTURE1, and pass it to the shader with the name "BloomTexture". If you don't know how do it, check the code in drawFullscreenPass().

In compose.frag:

  • Add the uniform texture sampler for "BloomTexture".
  • Sample the bloom texture and add the color to the HDR color, before tone-mapping.

Remember that you can increment the number of blur passes to get a more spread bloom value. Ideally we would use a larger blur kernel for that, but for this exercise it is ok.
Exercise 9.5
Cel-shading

Post processing can be also used to do non photorealistic rendering(NPR). As an example, we will do a quick cel-shading.

In this case we start with the final color, with textures, lighting, etc. already included. It is possible to discretize the color value in many ways. We could, for instance, just divide per component, but that would not have the best result.

We saw before an alternative color format (HSV) that could be useful here. We will divide in steps the channel V (value) so we can preserve the hue and saturation.

In main.cpp:

  • Find the section of the file prepared to render cel-shading. You may want to modify postFXMode default value so you don't have to use the UI every time to change mode.
  • Replace the copy pass with a pass for cel-shading. The shader this time is celshading_shader.
  • The source image for this effect will be the accumulation buffer.
  • We will render directly to the default framebuffer, so we don't need to bind any framebuffer.
  • The uniforms for this pass are:
    • exposure: We can also do tone-mapping in NPR techniques. Use the same exposure than in exercise 9.1.
    • steps: An integer specifying the number of steps in which we want to divide the colors. You should add this to the UI.

In celshading.frag:

  • Add the uniforms that you just added in C++.
  • Apply the exposure as we did before to get a color in range (0, 1).
  • Convert the color to HSV.
  • Multiply the V component by the steps, round it to an integer value, and divide by steps.
  • Finally, convert the color back to RGB.

That looks cool! It is not as clean as the one in exercise 6 because we are using very detailed textures, but it still looks like a cartoon/comic.
Exercise 9.6
Outline

In exercise 6 we saw a way to render an outline by adding an extra pass for each object, extruding the normals and culling front faces. In this exercise we will do the outline with post-processing.

To generate the outline we will detect if there is a difference in depth between neighboring pixels (left, right, up, down). It could be done detecting also difference in normals or in color, but with depth it will be enough.

In main.cpp:

  • Add a new fullscreen pass right after the Cel-shading, using the outline shader.
  • The source image for this pass is the depth g-buffer, and it will also render to default framebuffer, like the previous pass.
  • This pass requires blending to render on top of the previous framebuffer. For the blend function, use alpha blending (src alpha, 1 - src alpha).
  • The uniforms for this pass are:
    • scale: a vec2 that has the inverse of the width and height. You can get the framebuffer size with glfwGetFramebufferSize
    • outline color: the outline color. You should add this to the UI.
    • distance: a float value to decide when to add an outline. A good initial value could be 0.01f. You should add this to the UI.

In outline.frag:

  • Add the uniforms that you just added in C++.
  • Implement a function SampleDepth to read the depth from the texture and process it to be in a good range (there are many ways to do this, depending on the look you are going for). We recommend changing the depth to range (-1, 1) and then return the cubed value (depth*depth*depth). This will make the outline visible in mid-range but not far away.
  • Implement a function DetectEdge that will SampleDepth and compare the obtained value with the reference depth. For a good comparison, we suggest the absolute difference, divided by the distance uniform.
  • In main, sample depth a first time with offset (0, 0). This will be the reference value for other samples.
  • We are doing a loop to test the neighbor pixels. For each offset in the list we call DetectEdge and add it to the intensity, with some weight. We need to scale the offsets with the scale uniform, to adapt to the resolution.
  • Return in FragColor the outline color uniform in RGB, and the outline intensity you just computed (clamped between 0 and 1) as alpha.

How does this outline compare to the one in exercise 6? Which one do you like better? How would you change the thickness of the outline?
